{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11934"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11934"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.02,0.71,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4530"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1456"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44952"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man is brought in by ambulance to the Emergency Department with a single episode of prolonged vertigo. On waking that morning, he had felt like the room was spinning around but it soon subsided and he managed to drive to work. However, soon after arriving at work his vertigo got worse and was associated with nausea and unsteadiness. He has no other symptoms such as headache, hearing loss, tinnitus, paraesthesia or muscle weakness. He has recently recovered from an upper respiratory tract infection. His medical history includes tension headaches, obesity and depression. On HINTs test (Head Impulse, Nystagmus, and Test of Skew), he has an abnormal head impulse test with corrective saccades to midline with rotation of the head, horizontal nystagmus to the right, and test of skew absent for skew deviation. There are no focal neurological deficits on neurological examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Migraine","Acoustic neuroma","Cerebellar stroke","Vestibular neuritis","Labyrinthitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually triggered by a recent viral infection and affects the vestibular component of CN VIII. Symptoms include vertigo, unsteadiness and nausea. Treatment is targeted toward treating the symptoms as the illness will usually self-resolve. The HINTS examination consists of three components: Head Impulse, Nystagmus, and Test of Skew. It has been found to have high sensitivity and specificity for distinguishing peripheral from central vertigo in people presenting with acute vestibular syndrome when performed correctly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine \u003C/strong\u003Ewould usually involve other symptoms including a debilitating, unilateral headache, photo and phonophobia, and may also have a preceding aura.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcoustic neuromas\u003C/strong\u003E, which account for the majority of cerebellopontine angle tumours, are caused by the abnormal production of Schwann cells on the vestibulocochlear nerve and can present with varying symptoms including hearing loss, unsteadiness, aural fullness, headache and focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellar stroke \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect as on HINTS test, head impulse test would be normal with no corrective saccades. Nystagmus can be horizontal and direction changing, vertical or torsional. Test of skew would show skew deviation. There would also be focal neurological deficits such as ataxia, dysdiadochokinesis and dysmetria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabyrinthitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis inflammation of the inner ear and may cause hearing loss or tinnitus as both components of the vestibulocochlear nerve are affected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HINTS test is useful for distinguishing between peripheral from central vertigo"],"references":["\u0022Vestibular Schwannoma (Acoustic Neuroma) and Neurofibromatosis\u0022. NIDCD. 18 August 2015.","Ferri\u0027s Clinical Advisor 2016: 5 Books in 1. Elsevier Health Sciences. 2015. p. 735. ISBN 9780323378222.","Smith T, Rider J, Cen S, et al. Vestibular Neuronitis. [Updated 2022 Jul 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549866/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-28T16:54:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-28T16:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4530"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41961"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms"